<designnote>Same pattern as used for animate plurals, for inanimate			plurals.</designnote><explnote>To mark more than one of a thing (rather than a person),				for most (but definitely not all) words the ending is -l. This				comes out as -n if the word already ends in -n. This double -nn at				the end of a word can be hard to hear at first, so it is a good				idea to practice both saying it and listening for it.				Like with people, if the ending is added to -i or -u, those sounds come out as -i'				and -u', as in awti'l.			</explnote><timesig>@20120723-JW-RM-1thru25.wav@6:45-6:58.5</timesig><vocab>
